**First Solution**

You could just create a **`click`** event listener &amp; it would solve the issue like so:

```
$(function () {
  $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;).tooltip({
  	trigger: &#39;hover&#39;,
  });
  
  $(window).on(&#39;scroll&#39;, function() {
    $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;).tooltip(&#39;hide&#39;);
  });

  $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;).on(&#39;click&#39;, function() {
    $(this).tooltip(&#39;show&#39;);
  });
});
```

Obviously, you should refactor this code. It&#39;s for demonstration purposes only.

Check a **[working code sample here](https://jsfiddle.net/szhbt1nf/)**.

***Second Solution***

**Edit 1:**

If you want to **`disable`** the **`tooltip`** altogether on **mobile view**, you can check for **[window.innerWidth](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/innerWidth)** using the **[resize()](https://api.jquery.com/resize/)** jQuery method &amp; disabling it on **mobile view** like so:

```
$(function () {
    $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;).tooltip({
        trigger: &#39;hover&#39;,
    });
                         
    $(window).resize(function() {
        isMobileView = &#39;600&#39;;
        screenWidth = window.innerWidth;

        if (screenWidth &lt;= isMobileView) {
            $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;).tooltip(&#39;disable&#39;);
        } else {
            $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;).tooltip(&#39;enable&#39;);
        };
    });
});
```

Now the **`tooltip`** will be the disabled on screen sizes with less than **`600px`**

Check a **[working code sample here](https://jsfiddle.net/69sczL3f/)**. 

**Third Solution** 

**Edit 2:**

As you requested in your comment, you wish to **`disable`** the **`tooltip`&#39;s hover behavior** on *mobile screen* only. I found another solution for your use case, I like my **first solution** better since it also solves your use case &amp; needs less code. But it&#39;s your project after all &amp; you should know better than me.

My current solution is the following:

```
$(function () {
    const dataToggleTooltip = $(&#39;[data-toggle=&quot;tooltip&quot;]&#39;);

    dataToggleTooltip.tooltip({
        trigger: &#39;hover&#39;,
    });
    
    disableTooltipOnHover = () =&gt; {
        dataToggleTooltip.hover( function(){
            $(this).tooltip(&#39;hide&#39;);
        });

        dataToggleTooltip.on(&#39;click&#39;, function(){
            $(this).tooltip(&#39;show&#39;);
        });
    };

    enableTooltipOnHover = () =&gt; {
        dataToggleTooltip.mouseenter(function(){
            $(this).tooltip(&#39;show&#39;);
        });
        dataToggleTooltip.mouseleave(function(){
            $(this).tooltip(&#39;hide&#39;);
        });
    };

    checkScreenViewIsMobile = () =&gt; {
        isMobileView = &#39;600&#39;;
        screenWidth = window.innerWidth;

        if (screenWidth &lt;= isMobileView) {
            disableTooltipOnHover();
        } else {
            enableTooltipOnHover();
        };
    }

    $(document).ready(function(){
        checkScreenViewIsMobile();        
    });

    $(window).resize(function() {
        checkScreenViewIsMobile();
    });
});
```

*If you have any question about the code*, let me know &amp; I&#39;ll explain you with further details.

Check the **[working code sample](https://jsfiddle.net/mw0qcxfz/)**.

