Taking a number of 0 to N and converting it to 2 numbers of a grid (or more commonly a indices of a 2D array) is a common operation

For example

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const width = 5
    const count = 25;
    for (let i = 0; i &lt; count; ++i) {
      const x = i % width;
      const y = Math.floor(i / width);
      console.log(i, &#39;x:&#39;, x, &#39;y:&#39;, y);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Run the code above and look at the numbers printed in the console. They look like this

```
0 x: 0 y: 0
1 x: 1 y: 0
2 x: 2 y: 0
3 x: 3 y: 0
4 x: 4 y: 0
5 x: 0 y: 1
