19 x: 4 y: 3
20 x: 0 y: 4
21 x: 1 y: 4
22 x: 2 y: 4
23 x: 3 y: 4
24 x: 4 y: 4
```

The modulo operator `%` returns the remainder of division so for example `13 % 5` = `3`. `Math.floor` rounds down to the nearest integer value so `13 / 5` = `2.6` and so `Math.floor(2.6)` is just `2`

Note the code above can also be written like this

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const width = 5
    const count = 25;
    for (let i = 0; i &lt; count; ++i) {
      const x = i % width;
      const y = i / width | 0;
      console.log(i, &#39;x:&#39;, x, &#39;y:&#39;, y);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


Above I changed `Math.floor(i / width)` into `i / width | 0`. This takes advantage of the fact that &#39;|&#39; is the &quot;binary or&quot; operator and always converts values into integers. Doing a binary or with 0 does nothing so we&#39;re left with just the &quot;converting to integer&quot; part which for positive numbers returns the same values as `Math.floor`. 

I prefer this style, it&#39;s compact and it&#39;s also faster but some programmers prefer using `Math.floor` usually because they don&#39;t know about using the `| 0` idiom for rounding down but also because they feel like `Math.floor` is clearer.

